{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018sGVBs5H5R17NT4V87ik5z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the `host { }` block:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** — The default. Run inside a Docker container via `cloche-agent`.\n    10→Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the standard workflows for coding\n    11→tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** — Declared by including a `host { }` block in the workflow definition.\n    14→Run on the host machine as the daemon process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or\n    15→`workflow` type. The `workflow` step type dispatches a container workflow run and waits\n    16→for it to complete. This is the extension point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→Any `.cloche` file can contain host workflows — they are not restricted to a specific\n    19→filename. A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to\n    20→three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    21→\n    22→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    23→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    24→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    25→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    26→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    27→\n    28→Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n    29→automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the web dashboard) to\n    30→release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. Receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` for the\n    31→task to release.\n    32→\n    33→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    34→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    35→\n    36→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    37→object with the following fields:\n    38→\n    39→| Field | Required | Description |\n    40→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    41→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    42→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    43→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    44→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    45→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    46→\n    47→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    48→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    49→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    50→reassignment.\n    51→\n    52→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    53→file is a parse error.\n    54→\n    55→## Concepts\n    56→\n    57→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    58→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    59→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    60→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    61→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    62→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    63→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    64→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    65→\n    66→## Step Types\n    67→\n    68→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    69→\n    70→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    71→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    72→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    73→\n    74→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    75→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    76→\n    77→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    78→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (those with a `host { }` block).\n    79→\n    80→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    81→parse error.\n    82→\n    83→## DSL Syntax\n    84→\n    85→```\n    86→workflow \"develop\" {\n    87→  container {\n    88→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    89→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    90→  }\n    91→\n    92→  step implement {\n    93→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    94→    results = [success, fail]\n    95→  }\n    96→\n    97→  step test {\n    98→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  step fix {\n   103→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   104→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n   105→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   106→  }\n   107→\n   108→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   109→  implement:success -> test\n   110→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   111→  test:success      -> done\n   112→  test:fail         -> fix\n   113→  fix:success       -> test\n   114→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   115→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   116→}\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→## Key Properties\n   120→\n   121→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   122→field makes it a script step.\n   123→\n   124→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   125→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   126→\n   127→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   128→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   129→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   130→\n   131→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   132→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   133→\n   134→## Wire Output Mappings\n   135→\n   136→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   137→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→The general form:\n   144→\n   145→```\n   146→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   147→```\n   148→\n   149→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   150→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   151→\n   152→| Expression | Meaning |\n   153→|---|---|\n   154→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   155→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   156→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   157→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   158→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   159→\n   160→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   161→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   162→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   163→\n   164→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   165→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   166→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   167→\n   168→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   169→\n   170→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   171→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   172→\n   173→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   174→network allowlist.\n   175→\n   176→```\n   177→workflow \"develop\" {\n   178→  container {\n   179→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   180→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   181→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   182→  }\n   183→  ...\n   184→}\n   185→```\n   186→\n   187→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   188→\n   189→**`host {}`** — Declares a workflow as a host workflow. Can appear in any `.cloche` file.\n   190→Sets agent defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. An empty `host {}` block\n   191→(no keys) is valid and simply marks the workflow as host-side.\n   192→\n   193→```\n   194→workflow \"main\" {\n   195→  host {\n   196→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   197→  }\n   198→  ...\n   199→}\n   200→```\n   201→\n   202→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   203→\n   204→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   205→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   206→var > default `claude`.\n   207→\n   208→## Host Workflow Example\n   209→\n   210→A three-phase host workflow setup with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   211→workflows:\n   212→\n   213→```\n   214→# Host workflows — runs on the host machine\n   215→\n   216→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   217→  step fetch-tickets {\n   218→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   219→    results = [success, fail]\n   220→  }\n   221→\n   222→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   223→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   224→}\n   225→\n   226→workflow \"main\" {\n   227→  host {\n   228→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   229→  }\n   230→\n   231→  step prepare-prompt {\n   232→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   233→    results = [success, fail]\n   234→  }\n   235→\n   236→  step develop {\n   237→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   238→    results       = [success, fail]\n   239→  }\n   240→\n   241→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   242→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   243→  develop:success        -> done\n   244→  develop:fail           -> done\n   245→}\n   246→\n   247→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   248→  step push-for-review {\n   249→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   250→    results = [success, fail]\n   251→  }\n   252→\n   253→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   254→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   255→}\n   256→```\n   257→\n   258→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   259→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   260→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   261→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   262→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   263→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   264→\n   265→## Execution Model\n   266→\n   267→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   268→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   269→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   270→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   271→\n   272→**Host workflows** (those with a `host { }` block) are parsed and executed by the daemon\n   273→on the host machine. Any `.cloche` file may contain host workflows; the daemon\n   274→orchestrates them in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via\n   275→`sh -c` with the\n   276→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   277→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   278→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   279→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   280→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   281→points to the actual project directory.\n   282→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8cbfb090-0ebf-4a46-bf7f-bc05e67012f9","uuid":"e0101e84-2290-4c62-b8d1-c967238b0a36","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the `host { }` block:\n\n**Container workflows** — The default. Run inside a Docker container via `cloche-agent`.\nSteps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the standard workflows for coding\ntasks.\n\n**Host workflows** — Declared by including a `host { }` block in the workflow definition.\nRun on the host machine as the daemon process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or\n`workflow` type. The `workflow` step type dispatches a container workflow run and waits\nfor it to complete. This is the extension point for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nAny `.cloche` file can contain host workflows — they are not restricted to a specific\nfilename. A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to\nthree workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nAdditionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\nautomatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the web dashboard) to\nrelease a stale claimed task back to `open` status. Receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` for the\ntask to release.\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (those with a `host { }` block).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n  test:success      -> done\n  test:fail         -> fix\n  fix:success       -> test\n  fix:fail          -> abort\n  fix:give-up       -> abort\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n\nWorkflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\nsteps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n\n**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\nnetwork allowlist.\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n\n**`host {}`** — Declares a workflow as a host workflow. Can appear in any `.cloche` file.\nSets agent defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. An empty `host {}` block\n(no keys) is valid and simply marks the workflow as host-side.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n\nStep-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\nresolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\nvar > default `claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase host workflow setup with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# Host workflows — runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** (those with a `host { }` block) are parsed and executed by the daemon\non the host machine. Any `.cloche` file may contain host workflows; the daemon\norchestrates them in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via\n`sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":282,"startLine":1,"totalLines":282}}}
